<node><name>Set up with Different Frequencies</name>
<id>11</id>
<lefticon>undefined</lefticon>
<righticon>orchestration</righticon>
<column>ICI</column>
<textHTML>&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Initiate discussion about the effect of 2 waves of different frequencies interfering at one location&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Derive the equation, mathematically, and highlight the beat frequency and the average pitch&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Use a simulation to show the beat pattern and emphasize that describing what you hear when dealing with beats is not intuitive&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Set up two signal generators, each feeding into separate speakers and each using different frequencies (e.g. use 240 and 244 Hz)&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Place the microphone and the sound sensor close to the speakers&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;</textHTML>
<linkedwf>undefined</linkedwf>
<textheight>258</textheight>
<isdropped>true</isdropped>
</node>
<node><name>Observe Sound Effects</name>
<id>12</id>
<lefticon>class</lefticon>
<righticon>analyze</righticon>
<column>ICS</column>
<textHTML>&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Using the sound sensor (and computer pasco software), notice 2 peaks, one for each of the frequencies&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Using the microphone (connected to the oscilloscope), notice the same pattern as that on the simulation&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;While hearing the beats, observe the patterns&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;</textHTML>
<linkedwf>undefined</linkedwf>
<textheight>146</textheight>
